        "comment": {
            "name": "comment",
            "type": "com.atlassian.jira.issue.fields.CommentSystemField",
            "value": [
                {
                    "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/comment\/29332",
                    "author": {
                        "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/user?username=thomas",
                        "name": "thomas",
                        "displayName": "Thomas Weidner",
                        "active": true
                    },
                    "body": "I never heard that toString() returns an object.\nEven in Java toString() returns a string and not a object.",
                    "updateAuthor": {
                        "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/user?username=thomas",
                        "name": "thomas",
                        "displayName": "Thomas Weidner",
                        "active": true
                    },
                    "created": "2009-03-08T13:39:46.000+0000",
                    "updated": "2009-03-08T13:39:46.000+0000"
                },
                {
                    "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/comment\/29333",
                    "author": {
                        "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/user?username=jhartikainen",
                        "name": "jhartikainen",
                        "displayName": "Jani Hartikainen",
                        "active": true
                    },
                    "body": "I believe what this is after is making Zend_Date immutable.\n\nThough I'm having difficulties finding the \"programming standards\" the reporter is talking about.",
                    "updateAuthor": {
                        "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/user?username=jhartikainen",
                        "name": "jhartikainen",
                        "displayName": "Jani Hartikainen",
                        "active": true
                    },
                    "created": "2009-03-08T15:35:42.000+0000",
                    "updated": "2009-03-08T15:35:42.000+0000"
                },
                {
                    "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/comment\/29335",
                    "author": {
                        "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/user?username=thomas",
                        "name": "thomas",
                        "displayName": "Thomas Weidner",
                        "active": true
                    },
                    "body": "When I have a date and make calculations I expect the calculations to take place.\n\n{code}\n$date = new Zend_Date();\n$date->addWeek(1)->subDay(2)->setYear(2008);\nprint $date->getIso();\n{code}\n\nIn the above case I expect the date object to hold the calculated value. Why should I be forced to save the return value to a new variable and expect the date object not to be changed ?\n\nWhen I don't want to change the date object I have to clone it as within every language. This preserves the original object\/instance.\n\n{code}\n$date = new Zend_Date();\n$date2 = clone $date;\n$date->addWeek(1)->subDay(2)->setYear(2008);\nprint $date->getIso();\nprint $date2->getIso();\n{code}",
                    "updateAuthor": {
                        "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/user?username=thomas",
                        "name": "thomas",
                        "displayName": "Thomas Weidner",
                        "active": true
                    },
                    "created": "2009-03-09T00:12:51.000+0000",
                    "updated": "2009-03-09T00:12:51.000+0000"
                },
                {
                    "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/comment\/29340",
                    "author": {
                        "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/user?username=mist",
                        "name": "mist",
                        "displayName": "mist",
                        "active": false
                    },
                    "body": "OK, here's some comment again... :)\n\n1) I apologize for useing 'programming standards', I admit that the use of it is not correct. \n2) I wanted to use the Zend_Date in a calendar, and it's really annoying if you have to clone each time, just to make a button that refers to the next\/previous daay\/week\/month\/year\n3) I didn't necessary mean to make Zend_Date immutable after creation. That would be some kind of overkill, I think...\n4) I don't see much benefit of add\/subtract methods in this context. I would use setters for setting a state of an object (setDay($this->getDay() + 1)), I would use add\/sub-methods for returning a new object. \nAs a solution you could add another parameter (boolean) to the add\/sub methods to tell whether it should modify the object or return a modified clone of itself. \n\nAnd as a small side note:  the source code of Zend_Date is REALLY unreadable... :s (the _calculate() method is about 1300 lines!) that's a pity (but this is a personal feeling, I don't know how other people think about this :))",
                    "updateAuthor": {
                        "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/user?username=mist",
                        "name": "mist",
                        "displayName": "mist",
                        "active": false
                    },
                    "created": "2009-03-09T08:49:18.000+0000",
                    "updated": "2009-03-09T08:49:18.000+0000"
                },
                {
                    "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/comment\/29372",
                    "author": {
                        "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/user?username=thomas",
                        "name": "thomas",
                        "displayName": "Thomas Weidner",
                        "active": true
                    },
                    "body": "The fact that you can't read the code of Zend_Date and don't know how date calculations work internally has nothing to do with this issue.",
                    "updateAuthor": {
                        "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/user?username=thomas",
                        "name": "thomas",
                        "displayName": "Thomas Weidner",
                        "active": true
                    },
                    "created": "2009-03-10T11:45:12.000+0000",
                    "updated": "2009-03-10T11:45:12.000+0000"
                },
                {
                    "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/comment\/29373",
                    "author": {
                        "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/user?username=thomas",
                        "name": "thomas",
                        "displayName": "Thomas Weidner",
                        "active": true
                    },
                    "body": "Definetly no:\nThe adder, subber and setter methods work always for the object. This will not be changed.\nAdding a day means that this object is altered.\n\nThere is no benefit for users to have 400 new lines just to have an optional parameter which changes OOP behaviour in a way which is a bad coding standard.\n\nYou could simply extend Zend_Date and change the needed add\/sub methods to return what you need.",
                    "updateAuthor": {
                        "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/user?username=thomas",
                        "name": "thomas",
                        "displayName": "Thomas Weidner",
                        "active": true
                    },
                    "created": "2009-03-10T11:49:56.000+0000",
                    "updated": "2009-03-10T11:49:56.000+0000"
                },
                {
                    "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/comment\/29374",
                    "author": {
                        "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/user?username=thomas",
                        "name": "thomas",
